msItem.title: Common Pleas entries
msItem.note: The entries mostly date to c. 1435-1445 and are interspersed with miscellaneous precedents and notes, including later entries going up to the 1470s; for more details of the legal items among these entries, see Baker and Ringrose (1996), pp. 161-162.
The collection was evidently compiled by Simon Elryngton since he features as attorney in some of the entries.
Among the entries are some precedents that are not Common Pleas, for a discussion of these items see Baker and Ringrose (1996), p. 162.

p.secFol: ii recto Inquisicio captus apud Chelmesford

extent.seg:
2 + 341 + 2 leaves.
The endleaves at the beginning have been foliated ff. 1-2 and those at the end ff. 21-22. The core leaves include f. 12, a parchment stub with writing, a fragmentary leaf (f. v a), and leaves omitted in the 15th-century foliation sequence (ff. cvii a-f, cxxiii a-d, cxlvii a, clxvi a, clxvi a, clxviii a, and ccx a). However, unfoliated blank stubs after ff. cxiii, cxix, ccxlvii, cclxxvii, cclxxviii, and ccxciii are not included in this count.

foliation.p: 1-2 + 3-20, i-v, v a, vi-cvii, cvii a-cvii f, cviii-cxxiii, cxxiii a-cxxiii d, cxxiv-cxlvii, cxlvii a, cxlviii-clxvi, clxvi a, clxvii-clxviii, cxlviii a, clxix-ccx, ccx a, ccxi-ccxlix, cclx-cccxviii + 21-22

The foliation sequence stated above is the one currently in use for this volume (as of December 2022). It comprises a mixture of 15th-, 20th- and 21st-century numbering (see below for further, detailed description of each). Folios 1-2 are the front pastedown (now lifted) and endleaf; 21-22 are the rear endleaf and pastedown (still stuck down).

The main portion of the manuscript had originally been foliated using Roman numerals in the 15th century, with various errors or inconsistencies -
the same number used twice (ff. cxlvii, clxvi, ccx)
gaps left (after ff. cvii, clxviii)
blank leaves left unfoliated (after ff. v, cxxiii)
a jump in numbering (from f. ccxlix to cclx)
leaves that were not numbered but after which the foliation sequence continued as if they had been (after ff. ccxxvii and ccxlvi) - and leaving the latter part of the manuscript (after f. cclxiii) and accompanying matter at both ends of the volume unnumbered.

In the 20th century, an attempt was made by Basil Atkinson to fill some of these gaps. Atkinson numbered the leaves after ff. cvii using lower case letters: so ff. cvii, cvii a-cvii f. He also continued the sequence of Roman numerals for the remaining leaves in the main section of the manuscript, and used Arabic numerals for the accompanying matter at each end. However, a mistake was made in the sequence of Roman numerals: starting with 'cclxiv', Atkinson continued the sequence up to 'cclxxiii' but on the next leaf accidentally slipped back ten digits to 'cclxiv', which error persisted for the rest of the main section of the volume.

In 2022, in preparation for the manuscript's digitisation, the decision was taken to correct this recent mistake and ensure that all other leaves in the volume were assigned a folio number, as follows:
Where the same number was used twice in the 15th-century sequence, the second leaf was marked 'a': so, f. cxlvii is followed now by f. cxlvii a; f. clxvi by f. clxvi a; f. ccx by f. ccx a.
Where gaps had been left and the numbering continued incorrectly, the omitted leaf was marked 'a': so, ff. clxviii, clxviii a.
Where blank leaves had been left unfoliated, the omitted leaves were marked using lower case letters: so, f. cxxii is now followed by ff. cxxiii a-cxxiii d.
Where there was a jump in the 15th-century foliation, this has been left as it: so, f. ccxlix is followed by cclx.
Where leaves were not numbered but the foliation sequence continues as if they had been, numbers have been written onto these leaves accordingly: so, f. ccxxvii is followed by ff. ccxxviii and ccxxix, and f. ccxlvi is followed by ccxlvii.
Atkinson's foliation has been cancelled from the point of his mistake onwards (so, after f. cclxxiii) and the numbering continued correctly: so f. cclxxiii is followed by ff. cclxxiv through to cccxviii. The following imperfect leaves were also foliated:
f. 12: this had been counted in Atkinson's sequence but not physically numbered.
f. v a As per standard practice at the University Library, stubs have not been numbered. These changes were made in pencil in the upper right-hand corner of the rectos, on 17 November 2022, by James FreemanFreeman, James, Medieval Manuscripts Specialist, Cambridge University Library.

foliation.note: Numbering in Roman numerals, written in brown ink in the upper right-hand corner of the rectos, perhaps by Simon Elryngton.
Numbering in pencil in the upper right-hand corner of the rectos, by the hand of B.F.C. Atkinson Atkinson, Basil Ferris Campbell, now partially struck out and corrected (see below).

collation.p: The collation is unestablished due to tight binding, but the manuscript consists of a large number of small quires of two, four, six, or eight leaves.

supportDesc.condition: The manuscript's leaves are of uneven size, shape and thickness throughout the manuscript. The text on ff. clxix-cclxviii has been affected by damp or liquid stains. The manuscript features a strip of conservation paper in the lower half of f. xxxvii verso; and a loose blank strip of parchment in the gutter between f. cclxxxiii and f. cclxxxiv. Dried plant materials (stems) have been placed in the gutters between f. cxlvi and f. cxlvii, and f. cxlvii and f. cxlviia.

layout.seg: Occasional frame-ruling in crayon or pencil. Written in single columns. 18-55 lines to the page.

handNote.p: Written in many different cursive hands, all of them writing in Anglicana scripts with Secretary features.

decoDesc.p: The manuscript does not feature any significant decoration.

binding.p: 18th-century Bowtell-style half russia, light brown speckled paper sides; red lable on spine lettered Precedents M.S.. The spine encases that of a medieval binding with original sewing onto five double thongs, possibly split bands of alum-tawed leather, and endbands worked with blue and (?) red silk, now faded.
Binding height: 265 mm; width: 180 mm; depth: 70 mm.

origin.origDate: Written in the second half of the 15th century.

provenance.p: 1r-22r: Simon Elryngham of Hackney (d. 1481/85) Elryngham, Simon, d. 1481/85, attorney of the Common Pleas and filazer of that court for Norfolk, 1442-1475: compiled and owned the manuscript as indicated by a rubrics on f. 4r: Kalendare istius libri factum per Simonem Elrygnton and f. 8v: Simon Elryngton de Hakeney deo gracias; and ownership inscriptions on f. clxxiv verso: Liber Simonis Elryngton filiciarii Norff. in Communi Banco ihc. mercy; f. cclxiv verso: Liber S. Elryngton de Hakeney; f. cclxvi verso: Explicit quod Simon Elrygnton possessor totius libri etc. ihc.

Simon Elryngton perhaps passed the manuscript down to his son John Elryngton (d. 1504)Elryngton, John (d. 1504), filazer for Hampshire and Wiltshire from 1460 to 1475, and then for London and Middlesex, deputy Custos Brevium as suggested by the item on f. 21v.
1r-22r: Tamezen Grenham Grenham, Tamezen: her name inscribed in a 16th-century script on f. 22r: Tamezen Grenham and Alles her dowter.

history.acquisition: Presented to the University Library in 1715 by George I George I, King of Great Britain, 1660-1727 : possibly once featured the donation bookplate engraved by John Pine Pine, John, 1690-1756 in 1736 on f. inside of the upper cover, but it is no longer present..

Owen Owen, A.E.B., now held in the University Archives (UA ULIB 7/3/72).
